Mouse developmental stage that covers the period from birth until late adulthood.
Embryonic neurula stage during which the neural plate formation occurs and the allantoic bud elongates .
Embryonic neurula stage during which the neural plate formation occurs and the head folds are formed while the neural groove becomes visible.
Embryonic neurula stage during which the neural plate formation occurs and the head folds continue to enlarge while the foregut pocket begins to form.
Theiler developmental stage 9 defined by advanced endometrial reaction and during which the egg-cylinder stage advances with the first evidence of an embryonic axis.
Theiler developmental stage 9 defined by advanced endometrial reaction and during which the first mesodermal cells are produced by gastrulation late in this stage.
Theiler developmental stage 10 during which the tissue at the posterior end of the primitive streak bulges into the pro-amniotic cavity and forms the amniotic fold.

definition.value: Refers to MS (mid-streak) stage in Downs and Davies staging of gastrulating mouse embryos (PMID: 8269852, 1993).

value.value: Theiler developmental stage 10 during which small cavities coalesce to form a single cavity in the mesoderm of the posterior amniotic fold, the exocoelom.

definition.value: Refers to MS-LS (mid-streak to late streak) stage in Downs and Davies staging of gastrulating mouse embryos, 1993 (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8269852).

value.value: Theiler developmental stage 10 during which the allantoic bud first appears, gastrulation continues and the node becomes visible.

definition.value: Refers to MS-LS (mid-streak to late streak) stage in Downs and Davies staging of gastrulating mouse embryos, 1993 (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8269852).

value.value: Theiler developmental stage 12 defined by unturned embryo with first appearance of somite pairs 1-4 and during which the allantois extends further into the exocoelom. Maxillary components of the 1st branchial arch become prominent. The preotic sulcus is visible in the 2-3 somite embryo. The cardiogenic plate begins to form and the foregut pocket is clearly visible.

definition.value: Embryonic age 8 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage09.

value.value: Theiler developmental stage 12 defined by unturned embryo with first appearance of somite pairs 5-7 and during which neural closure occurs in the region of the 4th and 5th somites, extending in both directions from this site. Headfolds are particularly prominent. Optic placodes are first evident and become indented to form the optic pits. The heart rudiment develops rapidly. The allantois contacts the chorion at the end of this stage.

definition.value: Embryonic age 8 dpc (day post coitum). Refers to human CarnegieStage09.

value.value: Mouse developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult mouse which is over 6 weeks old.

Embryonic neurula stage during which the neural plate formation occurs and the amniotic cavity is sealed off into three distinct cavities - the amniotic cavity, the exocoelom and the ectoplacental cleft.

Mature stage that refers to an adult mouse which is over 18 months old.

definition.value: Mice from 18 months are considered as old and show presence of senescent changes in almost all biomarkers (see https://www.jax.org/news-and-insights/jax-blog/2017/november/when-are-mice-considered-old).

value.value: Prime adult stage that refers to a mouse which is over 10 and under 18 months old.

definition.value: Mice middle-aged group is used in the literature to investigate progressive age-related changes. For sake of consistency in age continuity, we adapt the age limits from https://www.jax.org/news-and-insights/jax-blog/2017/november/when-are-mice-considered-old.

value.value: Mature stage that refers to a adult mouse which is over 6 weeks and under 18 months old.

definition.value: Mice over 18 months old are considered as old (see https://www.jax.org/news-and-insights/jax-blog/2017/november/when-are-mice-considered-old).

value.value: Mature stage that refers to a mouse which is over 3 and under 7 months old.

definition.value: This stage is often used as the reference group for any age change in aging studies. Correlates to humans from 20 - 30 years old (see https://www.jax.org/news-and-insights/jax-blog/2017/november/when-are-mice-considered-old).
